b) Finding Optimal degree using Cross Validation

Here, we use the caret package to train a polynomial model based on repeated k-fold cross validation. We use k = 10 and repeat the run 10 times.

# Setting up 10-fold cross-validation 
set.seed(1998)

# Define the control for cross-validation
control <- trainControl(method = "repeatedcv", repeats = 10, number = 10)

# Train polynomial models with cross-validation using for loop
degrees <- 1:3

# Initialize for loop
for (d in degrees) {
name <- paste0("fit_cv_", d)
fit_cv_formula <- as.formula(paste0("nox ~ poly(dis, ", d, ")"))
fit_cv <- train(fit_cv_formula, data = Boston, method = "lm",
                trControl = control)
assign(name, fit_cv)
}

# Review the results
resamps <- resamples(list(deg1 = fit_cv_1,
                          deg2 = fit_cv_2,
                          deg3 = fit_cv_3))

summary(resamps)

d) Try different sizes of subset of predictors when fitting RF

The default m for mtry value is set to p/3. Try smaller and larger m values and see how this affects the test error. Also, report the numerical MSE values used in building the different rf models.

We can compare different rf models using a for loop.

# Initialize predictor
mtry_seq <- 1:10
rf.models <- list()

# Construct For loop
for (mtry in mtry_seq) {
  set.seed(1998)  
  model <- randomForest(Sales ~ ., data = train, mtry = mtry)
  rf.models[[mtry]] <- model
}

# Calculate MSE values

mse_values <- numeric(length(mtry_seq))
names(mse_values) <- mtry_seq

for (mtry in mtry_seq) {
  pred_rf <- predict(rf.models[[mtry]], newdata = test)
  mse_values[mtry] <- mean((pred_rf - Sales.test)^2)
}

# Viewing the MSE for each mtry value
mse_values

##        9       10 
## 2.572568 2.515455

We see that when we use all 10 predictors, the test MSE is the lowest at 2.51455.

Digression - Using train() function from caret package to find optimal mtry value

# Use train() function from `caret` package

# Set control for 10-fold cross validation
control <- trainControl(method = "cv", number = 10)

# Define Tune Grid for `mtry` values
mtry_grid <- expand.grid(.mtry = 1:10)

# Train model
set.seed(1998)
rf_models <- train(Sales ~ ., data = train, method = 'rf', trControl = control, tuneGrid = mtry_grid)

b) Create training set of first 200 observations and test set of remaining observations

# Split dataset into train/test set
train <- Hitters_v2[1:200,]

c) Boosting

Perform boosting on the training set with 1,000 trees for the range of values of the shrinkage parameter λ below. Produce a plot with different shrinkage values on the x-axis and the corresponding training set MSE on the y-axis.

(Use λ = (0.0001, 0.0002, 0.0005, 0.001, 0.002, 0.005, 0.01, 0.02, 0.05, 0.1, 0.2), with “interaction.depth=4” for (c) and (d).)

# Set up grid for shrinkage parameter and initialize mse
lambda_values <- c(0.0001, 0.0002, 0.0005, 0.001, 0.002, 0.005, 0.01, 0.02, 0.05, 0.1, 0.2)
mse_train <- numeric(length(lambda_values))
names(mse_train) <- lambda_values

# Perform boosting using gbm() function. Set seed for reproducibility
for (i in seq_along(lambda_values)) {
  set.seed(1998) 
  model_boosting <- gbm(Salary ~ ., data = train, distribution = "gaussian",
               n.trees = 1000, interaction.depth = 4,
               shrinkage = lambda_values[i])
  Salary_preds <- predict(model_boosting, train, n.trees = 1000)
  mse_train[i] <- mean((Salary_preds - train$Salary)^2)
}

mse_train
##        1e-04        2e-04        5e-04        0.001        0.002        0.005 
## 1.882170e+05 1.585060e+05 9.618853e+04 4.545062e+04 1.733735e+04 7.764863e+03 
##         0.01         0.02         0.05          0.1          0.2 
## 4.571851e+03 2.228893e+03 3.840433e+02 2.285804e+01 6.352354e-01

Notice we use distribution = "gaussian" because we are dealing with regression. We would use distribution = "binomial" if we were to solve a classification problem.

Now we produce a plot with different shrinkage values and training set MSE on the y-axis

# Data frame for plotting
plot_data <- data.frame(lambda = lambda_values, MSE = mse_train)

# Construct plot using ggplot2
ggplot(plot_data, aes(x = lambda, y = MSE)) +
  geom_line() +
  geom_point() +
  scale_x_log10() +
  labs(title = "Training MSE vs. Shrinkage", x = "Shrinkage (λ)", y = "Training MSE")

We see a monotonic decreasing curve of MSE as shrinkage increases.

d) Generate plot using Test MSE

# Set up grid for shrinkage parameter and initialize mse
lambda_values <- c(0.0001, 0.0002, 0.0005, 0.001, 0.002, 0.005, 0.01, 0.02, 0.05, 0.1, 0.2)
mse_test <- numeric(length(lambda_values))
names(mse_test) <- lambda_values

# Perform boosting using gbm() function. Set seed for reproducibility
for (i in seq_along(lambda_values)) {
  set.seed(1998) 
  model_boosting <- gbm(Salary ~ ., data = train, distribution = "gaussian",
               n.trees = 1000, interaction.depth = 4,
               shrinkage = lambda_values[i])
  Salary_preds <- predict(model_boosting, test, n.trees = 1000)
  mse_test[i] <- mean((Salary_preds - test$Salary)^2)
}

mse_test
##      1e-04      2e-04      5e-04      0.001      0.002      0.005       0.01

##       0.02       0.05        0.1        0.2

# Data frame for plotting

  geom_line() +
  geom_point() +
  scale_x_log10() +
  labs(title = "Test MSE vs. Shrinkage", x = "Shrinkage (λ)", y = "Test MSE")

As expected, we observe that the curve is not monotonic; the Test MSE decreases up to a certain shrinkage value and then starts to increase.

We can also visualize by plotting two curves in a single plot. To do so, we first convert wide format to long format, which is more consistent with ggplot2’s philosophy of mapping various aesthetics to a single variable.

# Reshaping the dataframe from wide to long format
long_data <- melt(plot_data, id.vars = 'lambda', variable.name = 'Type', value.name = 'MSE')

# Construct plot
ggplot(long_data, aes(x = lambda, y = MSE, color = Type)) +
  geom_line() +
  geom_point() +
  scale_x_log10() +
  labs(title = "MSE vs. Shrinkage", x = "Shrinkage (λ)", y = "MSE") +
  theme_minimal() +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("MSE" = "blue", "MSE2" = "red"))

The value of test MSE using the default options of the randomForest() function is 8760.0015444, which is larger than the minimum test MSE value derived from the boosting method, which is 2839.0564341

Q4) K-Means Algorithm from scratch

We build four functions in order to build the K-Means Algorithm

  1. initialize_centroids(): Randomly sample k data points and set them as initial centroids.
  2. cluster_assignment(): Assign clusters for all data points based on Euclidean distance.
  3. update_centroids(): Update new centroids by taking mean of all points within each cluster.
  4. K_means(): algorithm that takes parameters data, k, max_iter = 100 and incorporate aforementioned custom functions.
# Initialize centroids

initialize_centroids <- function(data, k) {
  sample(nrow(data), k)
}

# Construct cluster_assignment function
cluster_assignment <- function(data, centroids) {
  apply(data, 1, function(point) {
    distances <- apply(centroids, 1, function(centroid) {
      sqrt(sum((point - centroid)^2))
    })
    which.min(distances)
  })
}

Some points to notice.

  • cluster_assignment() function returns a vector of integers that correspond to the cluster assignments of each data point.
  • initialize_centroids() returns a vector of centroid indices. Thus, we use the below code to find the actual centroids.
centroids_idx <- initialize_centroids(data, k)
centroids <- data[centroids_idx, , drop = FALSE]

We add the drop = FALSE argument so we can maintain the structure (i.e., data frame) even if the subsetting results in a single row/column object.

Now we move on to the next custom function.

# Construct update_centroids() function
update_centroids <- function(data, clusters, k) {
  new_centroids <- matrix(nrow = k, ncol = ncol(data))
  for (i in 1:k) {
    new_centroids[i, ] <- colMeans(data[clusters == i, , drop = FALSE])
  }
  new_centroids
}

Since each row is an observation, we use colMeans() function to take the mean of all data points (calculate mean across columns).

Finally, taking all the above functions, together, we build the K-means algorithm.

# Construct k-means algorithm
K_means <- function(data, k, max_iter = 100) {
  centroids_idx <- initialize_centroids(data, k)
  centroids <- data[centroids_idx, , drop = FALSE]
  
  for (i in 1:max_iter) {
    clusters <- assign_clusters(data, centroids)
    new_centroids <- update_centroids(data, clusters, k)
    
    if (all(centroids == new_centroids)) break
    centroids <- new_centroids
  }
  
  list(centroids = centroids, clusters = clusters)
}

Next, we compute the objective value, which is the sum of the squared distances between each point and the centroid of its assigned cluster.

We do this in a two step process. First, we construct a custom defined function to compute the distances. Then, we apply the function to our data.

# Build function to calculate distances
compute_distance <- function(data, clusters, centroids) {
  total_distance <- 0
  for (i in 1:nrow(data)) {
    cluster <- clusters[i]
    point <- data[i, ]
    centroid <- centroids[cluster, ]
    total_distance <- total_distance + sum((point - centroid)^2)
  }
  return(total_distance)
}

compute_distance(x, initial_clusters, initial_centroids)
## [1] 8010.504

The objective value is 8010.5040875.

We can see that the updated centroids represent a much better cluster center than the initial centroids. We confirm this fact via the new objective value.

compute_distance(x, initial_clusters, centroids_v2)
## [1] 1830.288

The new objective value is 1830.2879822, which is a decrease of 6180.2161053 compared to the objective value calculated using initial centroids.
